## Git & GitHub Access

You may have a per-agent git Personal Access Token (PAT) configured by the user.
When configured, the following files are present inside your container:

| File                          | Contents                          |
|-------------------------------|-----------------------------------|
| `/run/secrets/git-pat`        | The PAT (treat as secret)         |
| `/run/secrets/git-username`   | Username (only when ≠ `git`)      |
| `/run/secrets/git-repo-url`   | The repo URL the user configured  |

**Always check for these files before assuming you have or lack git access.** A
plain `ls /run/secrets/` tells you what's configured. If `git-pat` is missing,
politely ask the user to set it via the **Git** tab in their AgentDrawer; do
NOT try to use other credentials.

### Cloning, pulling, pushing

`GIT_ASKPASS` is pre-set, so plain git commands authenticate automatically — no
manual auth step needed:

```bash
REPO=$(cat /run/secrets/git-repo-url)
git clone "$REPO" /tmp/repo
cd /tmp/repo && git pull
```

### GitHub REST API (issues, PRs, etc.)

For anything that isn't a `git` operation — listing issues, reading PRs, opening
issues — use the GitHub REST API with the PAT as a Bearer token:

```bash
PAT=$(cat /run/secrets/git-pat)
REPO=$(cat /run/secrets/git-repo-url)
# Parse owner/repo out of an https://github.com/<owner>/<repo>(.git) URL
SLUG=$(echo "$REPO" | sed -E 's#https?://github.com/##; s#\.git$##')

# List open issues
curl -s -H "Authorization: Bearer $PAT" \
     -H "Accept: application/vnd.github+json" \
     "https://api.github.com/repos/$SLUG/issues?state=open"
```

**Never echo `$PAT` in your reply or write it to any file the user might see.**
The Bearer header above is the only place it should appear.

### When the user asks "what issues are open?" / "check the repo"

1. Read `/run/secrets/git-repo-url` — that's the configured repo.
2. Use the GitHub API call above (issues are an API thing, not a `git` thing).
3. Summarise titles + numbers; offer to open one if the user is interested.
